 with you at some formulaically derived price; basically the more of a =0At=
oken you want to buy, the higher the price you will pay for it.=0A=0AThe pe=
ople putting their tokens into the AMM smart contract =E2=80=94 locking the=
m up =0Ato support liquidity =E2=80=94 get paid a share of the fees and tra=
ding profits that =0Athe AMM generates. This is called =E2=80=9Cyield,=E2=
=80=9D in the crypto world. But one more =0Atraditional-finance way to thin=
k about it is that it isoption premium. If you =0Alock up money in an AMM, =
what you are doing is saying =E2=80=9CI will sell you one =0AEther for $3,3=
00, or two for $3,500, or three for $3,800,=E2=80=9D or whatever, some =0As=
chedule of formulaic demand. You are effectivelywriting options on some tok=
en, =0Aat different prices. And you expect to get paid some premium =E2=80=
=94 the yield =E2=80=94 for =0Awriting those options. And then if Ether goe=
s up to $6,000, you will sell all =0Aof the Ether that you locked up in the=
 AMM, and you will regret it (your =0Atrading losses will be bigger than yo=
ur yield), but maybe you won=E2=80=99t regret it =0Athat much, because in c=
rypto, charmingly, this risk iscalled =E2=80=9Cimpermanent loss=E2=80=9D =
=0A<https://www.coinbase.com/learn/crypto-glossary/what-is-impermanent-loss=
> so =0Amaybe you will think it=E2=80=99s impermanent.=0A=0AAnd InfinityPoo=
ls is basically: You can buy an asset (say, Ether), and you can =0Aalso buy=
put options on that asset, so you have no risk of liquidation. Put in =0A$1=
, borrow $999, buy $1,000 of Ether, buy a put option on Ether struck at $99=
9, =0Aand your total package =E2=80=94 your Ether plus the put option =E2=
=80=94 is always worth at =0Aleast $999, so you are never underwater on you=
r loan. InfinityPoolsdescribes =0Athis <https://docs.infinitypools.finance/=
protocol-overview/introduction> as =0A=E2=80=9Cpaying some interest upfront=
 (premium),=E2=80=9D andWu notes =0A<https://x.com/jonwu_/status/1880052136=
584921135>: =E2=80=9CLPs should also earn =0Asignificantly higher yields (i=
n theory) than providing for spot AMMs, given out =0Aof range liquidity is =
constantly being borrowed to protect levered positions.=E2=80=9D =0A=E2=80=
=9COut of range liquidity is constantly being borrowed=E2=80=9D means =E2=
=80=9Cyou are buying =0Aputs, and paying for them.=E2=80=9D=0A=0ADoes this =
=E2=80=94 =E2=80=9Cborrow money to buy a stock, and buy puts so that you ne=
ver get a =0Amargin call=E2=80=9D =E2=80=94 exist in traditional finance=3F=
 Oh sure! There are two relevant =0Aforms:=0A=0A * There is a reasonably st=
andard trade called a =E2=80=9Cfunded collar =0A<https://bloom.bg/4h4Gyxj>,=
=E2=80=9D where a bank lends you the money to buy stock and =0Aalso sells y=
ou a put against the stock. The trade guarantees that the bank will =0Aget =
paid back =E2=80=94 at maturity, either (1) the stock will be worth more th=
an the =0Aloan, and you can sell it to pay back the loan, or (2) it will be=
 worth less, =0Ayou will exercise the put, the bank will buy the stock at t=
he put price and the =0Aput price will pay back the loan [6]  <> =E2=80=94 =
and so there are no margin calls. As =0Athe name =E2=80=9Ccollar=E2=80=9D s=
uggests, ordinarily in this trade you will sell the bank a =0Acall option, =
giving up some upside in order to make the put option cheaper, but =0AI sup=
pose if you wanted to you could just pay for the put outright. =0A * This i=
s a call option. =E2=80=9CStock plus a put=E2=80=9D has the payoff profile =
of a call =0Aoption; my example trade is equivalent to buying a call option=
 on $1,000 of =0AEther, struck at $999. Obviously when you buy a call optio=
n you pay a premium, =0Awhich you lose if the call finishes out-of-the-mone=
y; that=E2=80=99s true here too. [7] =0A <> It is possible that =E2=80=9Cun=
limited leverage with no liquidation=E2=80=9D is more =0Apsychologically ap=
pealing than =E2=80=9Cbuy a call option.=E2=80=9D =0AAlso the Bally=E2=80=
=99s Chicago $250 share is essentially the same thing, though that =0Aone i=
